A Republican Strategy to Oppose Obama's Re-election
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policies with the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth by affirming that election fraud is rarer in the U.S. than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republicans’ attorneys have recorded only 300 electoral fraud cases in 10 years in the United States.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
In contrast to Canada, the US states are responsible for conducting the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, the majority of American governments have been promulgating new laws since 2009 that complicate the process for registration or balloting.
This phenomenon gained importance after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of suffrage in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the time periods for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a court file is available.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states that force voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible voters, do not hold a photo ID issued by any government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an ID card.
However, there are often more than a hundred dollars to pay to get the required ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of those with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This goes even further.
Students who are considered to be voters, who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates, are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who are more likely to vote for the republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs for elections.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for voting.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voices.
Because it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican lawmakers in eight states promoted legislation that abolished voter registration on Election Day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These limitations are not without consequences.
For example, the voter registration campaigns in the 2004 general election helped to register around 10 million citizens.
As a result of the measures adopted since 2009, the proportion of new voters registered in 2010 has decreased by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the time frame for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-American, even though they make up only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same goes for the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
By contrast, whites, who represented 76% of voters, made up only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passage of laws that restrict voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of Democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the display of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
The democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the adopted laws and see in them the clear goal of influencing the results in the states decisive for 2012.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that those states that passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required in the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is for sure: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Early detection of prostate cancer: should the test be done or not?
In fact, the PSA test sometimes shows faulty results, with false negative or also false positive results, which lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
This leads to greater hesitation of the already indecisive men for conducting early detection tests.
Should the test be done or not?
We got the opinion of two specialists.
In the studies conducted in the USA, there were numerous confounding factors between the control groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and make clear recommendations.
Another study, this time from Europe, concluded that there is a difference in the mortality of patients with and without early detection.
This study also showed that when followed after 12 years, the likelihood of metastasis formation is 30 to 40% higher if no early detection was performed.
Therefore, I recommend the test from the age of 50 years or 40 years if you have a direct relative who was already suffering from prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also at higher risk.
The most important thing is to make the right decision once a cancer has been detected.
There are cancers that are aggressive and others that are indolent.
The patient needs to be made really aware of the extent of the risk of his cancer by pointing out the possible options in which prostate cancer can remain untreated if he does not impair the quality of life in the long term, and in these cases it is more likely to opt for active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer do not receive treatment because their cancer is not aggressive and poses no threat to their lives.
They are suggested active monitoring and offered treatment as the disease progresses.
The criteria for deciding who should and should not be treated are being determined with increasing accuracy.
Therefore, I still recommend carrying out the test.
However, the most important thing is to talk to your doctor to determine whether or not it should be performed.
In collaboration with the International Society of Urology, Movember has developed a tool to assess the pros and cons of the PSA test.
