Analyzing the Higgs Boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson last summer has caused a certain stir, and for good reason.
Indeed, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model – our best or “least false” explanation of nature and the behavior of matter – but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for the physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
Moreover, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented at a major physics convention in Kyoto this week, but data is still lacking to be completely certain about it.
Nevertheless, let’s assume that it’s actually the Higgs, since there seems to be only a small risk of being mistaken, and let’s look at what it’s about.
There is an inevitable law in this world that makes it impossible for two objects to be in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try too hard, as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state", this "state" being largely composed of some of their properties.
Starting from this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and who obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons are moving, an evil band of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred - in any case, not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons, according to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which by the way is absolutely amazing), are divided into two groups: the mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
But it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, it is only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
This is because when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is “disturbed” exactly at this location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" in order for this boson to show up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little like a frozen pond whose surface could only be furrowed by a very large rock.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like CERN is required – the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! – to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the refrigerator on its own.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) have no mass.
What can all this research be “good for”, Mrs Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to verify the Standard Model (SM), and they also allow physicists to accurately investigate any discrepancies between observations and predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who desperately hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stuff some holes of the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great shortcomings, as it offers no explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found at CERN.
Impact
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there were none.
By the way: in the early 60s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle — who worked in the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous-wave laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 — has already told us that the laser was initially considered more of a “laboratory toy.”
Just imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras worldwide and earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it does mean that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
