53% of the patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their place of residence, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e., care that is intended to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, whether at home, hospital or a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Greater Montreal Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec’s health care that causes several palliative care specialists to be concerned about the passage of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent palliative care figures such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not efficient enough to ensure that all are entitled to quality palliative care before accepting euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days in great pain without any measures being taken to relieve her.
I fear that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients, despite the worst prognosis, obstinately until the last day.
Hél<0xC3><0xA8>ne Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she stopped arduous chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop treatment, she replied that she regretted giving up the fight, she said.
She told me I was finished!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not allowing this desire after their pain has been alleviated by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Palliative Care Society, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in putting the patient to sleep either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to put me to sleep,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
