After Bitcoin’s price peaked at $30 in June 2011, it fell to $2 five months later before rebounding to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade of real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes Bitcoin as “the virtual currency with the greatest success,” “competing with the dollar or euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies like the “credits” used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy (and sometimes trade back) by playing.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, each time the trade is controlled and processed by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously custodians of the ledger, auditors, money issuers, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
With the help of the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins traded are present in the public account ledger, which is spread throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done via a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege of adding that extra line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "hacked."
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay for cheating twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain without a link, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the problem will receive 50 Bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to one hundred millionth, which leaves a certain margin...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not affect the actual protocol,” assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for paying with real money and uses the network Bitcoin.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering with the help of this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others such as the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "Mega Closing Sale" was launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, strongly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its Paytunia system is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions, which are thus cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented at the dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just have to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat indicates, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are being rethought in favour of more horizontal systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to catch on, but 2013 could be a tipping point,” he predicts.
Incidentally, the ECB’s report provides for a reassessment of the various risks that are now considered to be high in the event of this currency’s success.
We left Afghanistan.
And after that?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the US are expected to follow by the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain possession of its territory, and for the Afghan people to decide their future without expecting anything from us.
In particular, we punished the Afghan peasants by viewing them as terrorists.
And ourselves with our 88 soldiers killed, as well as the wounded and the injured.
The Taliban consists of foreign extremists, former leaders who have fled to Pakistan, but often farmers who refuse to have an armed foreign presence, as in the days of the Soviets.
They want to defend their centuries-old and archaic traditions, even if they are joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks and Tajiks.
Tolerated, sometimes supported by local insurgents, the latter will no longer be there as Western countries become more discreet.
The withdrawal of the French troops from the base at Nijrab, which I observed from a hill planted with almond trees and financed by French loans, took place properly.
Truck and tank convoys flown over by helicopters have reached Kabul without being attacked.
From the end of 2014, there will be no more influx of Taliban into Kabul.
Since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996, conditions have changed.
At the time, Kabul was empty and the country was overrun by war due to the struggles of the various rebel groups.
Their seizure of power at that time was seen as a kind of liberation and return to security.
The Afghan women have paid the price for the obscurantism of the farmers overwhelmed by the organization Al-Qaeda, but their situation has not improved to this day.
Former mujahideen, the Afghan government and current Taliban have a common desire to keep the women in a subordinate position.
The main figures of the anti-Soviet war came back to power in 2001.
They have turned into traders by seizing government land to sell as building land to refugees from Iran and Pakistan, taking advantage of massive U.S. subcontracting.
They have discredited themselves, and most of them were not themselves involved in the fighting.
As I have heard in the campaigns, people want a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave the country, just like those who have benefited from American grants: the flight of capital is considerable.
Young people are fed up with war and its ideologies.
During their exile in Iran or Pakistan, they have had contact with the modern world, and have enjoyed its advantages.
About 65% of the population is under 25 years of age; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, which is one fifth of the total population.
In the cities, state schools are full of girls and boys.
These young people, who do not want to return to the obscurantism of the former parties or to the corruption of certain leaders, will have to be provided with jobs.
Everyone, including the armed parties, is obsessed with mobile phones; television, with its Turkish series depicting a modern world, is watched everywhere.
There is an army now.
Are the authorities under whose authority it will be placed considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already trying to restore the militias in the province, which will escape the power of the central government.
Afghanistan, the land of mountains with strong local identities, should have benefited from some decentralization using the example of Western nations, but by abolishing the office of Prime Minister, which had existed since the 1964 Constitution, the US wanted to make it a centralized state with strong presidential power.
President Karzai does not want any foreign controls, especially on the occasion of the elections scheduled for April 2014.
However, his country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and long before that.
Industries have not been rebuilt, there are no functioning dams and important irrigation systems have not been repaired.
Everything is imported; apart from fruits and vegetables, nothing is produced.
The private initiative will be given priority.
In a country devastated by 30 years of war, state control of infrastructures would have been necessary.
The rumor was spread that Afghanistan possessed immense natural resources.
This reinforces the impression that the Western countries were only there to take possession of it.
Mining is not possible without energy to process the iron or copper ore on site, or without means of transport for export over the mountains.
The Chinese have already almost left the copper mine of Mes Aynak, let the international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) do their excavations on the huge Buddhist site and remain the main employers of the province.
One day it will also be necessary for Afghanistan and Pakistan, largely dependent on imports and exports, to re-establish normal relations.
The withdrawal of French combat troops was completed on 20 November.
The new cooperation agreement provides for the continuation of traditional aids: girls' and boys' gymnasiums, French Institute at the universities, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support of the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, a service of "civil-military actions" of the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), which was discontinued in 2012, has carried out numerous charitable works and measures for the rehabilitation of agriculture in dozens of mountain villages and has been carried out by a small French non-governmental organization in order to try to "win the hearts and minds" and achieve the impossible task of reconciling aid and offensive actions.
These works, which required a large number of local workers, have helped to quell the uprising: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increasing agricultural land.
What souvenir do we leave behind after military spending of two billion euros?
A much more modest budget will help improve local living conditions, which are very hard in these valleys, often at an altitude of more than 2000 meters.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small-scale agricultural projects from municipalities in Kapisa Province.
In order for farmers to free themselves from the insurgency led by foreign groups, which they say is their wish, it would be necessary to continue to provide less, more well-controlled and more direct civilian aid to them.
A constitution with the crowbar in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given this plenary two additional months to complete its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has relied on a preliminary, multiple-amended text, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his “autocratic delirium” by continuing to “break his word” and “kick the law.”
On the part of its proponents, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, forcing the brothers to abandon their plan of explaining the text to the Egyptians, section by section.
For the president, it is also a way of regaining his public and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages across the country.
According to a recent interview with Time magazine, Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to a hasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited power of attorney", the latter should supposedly come to an end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constituent assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals have not complied with the request.
Shortly before the constitutional declaration in mid-November, they turned their backs on the idea that they had not been able to express their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
To reach the quorum, 11 people, deputy members, were added in all haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that most of the articles were adopted unanimously.
Commentators, by the way, found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed at the time of prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the clock of the constituent assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made a stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
"Humility" the liberals, who see this only as a propaganda blow.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which grants the University of Al-Azhar a consultative function, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is troubling because “the people who are called upon to make a statement have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
Here we can see the first signs of a theocracy.”
The fears of the liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
"At present, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics, some of whom have been trained in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who is writing a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He acknowledges, however, that there may be an ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers here in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question could be raised to what extent civil judges are competent to decide on this."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is heavily criticized for the far-reaching powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the military’s wishes, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Likewise, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights defense associations have called for.
The latter also share their fears about the text, which they consider to be a threat to freedom.
Blasphemy is being perpetuated, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no article refers to the protection of women anymore, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern comforts and unspoilt nature.
AIF gives you the top five reasons to visit Israel.
In front of the holy places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding feast, walking on the water, the stilling of the sea storm, and fishing.
It was here that Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
However, most of the sanctuaries are found in Jerusalem.
Here, believers follow the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path starts at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
According to the Christian view, this is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred site of the Jews - the Western Wall, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Take a trip to the top
The ruins of the fortress of Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rock face in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else brings an aerial cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters, there is the famous ski resort of Hermon, which attracts countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain, you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the mountain top.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
Not all of them can be visited in just one trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum not far from the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or Dead Sea scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean Desert are preserved, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There, the collection is exhibited by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the former visitors and bath attendants.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most harrowing chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the Children’s Memorial, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
Upon entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died are resounding.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for health
The three main recreational areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three locations there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Amazingly, bathing in the Red Sea is also done in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and is where you can bathe all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea, located 417 meters below sea level, is the lowest sea in the world.
Its turquoise-blue water has a high salinity and therefore even carries non-swimmers on the surface without any problems.
The surrounding countryside is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural brine) and healing mud, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to calm stressed nerves.
Touching the secrets of antiquity
These secrets are hidden in the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city passed the famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with which he led a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets, which are named after zodiac signs.
According to legend, Fortune is said to be held by all those who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds from all over Israel and even other countries at photo shoots.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city in Judea and the residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre now hosts evening concerts and operas.
Watchlist for tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the journey is not taken in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily exchanged for shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city, you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a high-speed tram and in Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stops that connects the lower city with the upper city.
Actually, it's an underground funicular.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the means of transport, which is enough for a trip of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is observed in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is at rest.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
Many cafés, restaurants and restaurants only serve kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without dandruff, and foods that contain both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you can choose from different dishes with mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel), as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are many well-fed cats that roam the streets comfortably and unmolested.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like lively places and do not say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, prior to the lifting of the visa requirement on February 9, 2011.
'The Great and Powerful' Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MEPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with fake certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the remaining families in the home.
On December 1, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule only applies to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing sector and in the retail trade.
However, over time, the tests are to become mandatory for all guest workers, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
In doing so, you have to take not only language tests, but also tests into Russian history and the foundations of the legislation.
Language skills must be proven both for obtaining and extending the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who have received their training certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Purpose, problems and protection of rights
The total number of examination centres will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of Friendship of Peoples, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; more than 160 centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, posed the following question in the press several times before the law came into force: What does the whole thing actually mean?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, counter-speakers of the migration authority, the aim is to reduce the number of forced labourers.
“Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers,” said Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency’s representation in Tajikistan.
However, your rights must be protected before you leave.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical expertise encounter problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who, under the pretext of help, will put him in a dark, narrow barracks where he will endure with dozens of his peers for months without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive a lot of complaints from our migrants.
"At home, you are promised one thing, and on arrival you will be cheated, your passports will be taken away and you will not receive the promised wage," confirms the head of the head of the labor migration department of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't yell at me, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to earn their money in Russia, admit that they not only do not master the language of the target country, but also can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmens, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a reasonable primary education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to earn money.
“It’s difficult without language skills,” they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect regarding the law.
Only migrants with legal status are required to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of guest workers remain illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Access for Unauthorized Persons Prohibited"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, the linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be done quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and then cases of extortion arise.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told journalists.
"Just don't shy away from the cost of false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants can be forged.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The forged papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive these in vain: every migrant who hoped to be able to avoid the tests thus paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice the cost of the official test: it costs one migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates can not be easily purchased, both officials and civil rights activists agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test the first time that they will get time for a basic language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered positions in areas where no active communication with people is necessary.
Home Office Ignores Illegal Weapons Market
Proportion of legal weapons in crime extremely low
The Russian Interior Ministry is planning to tighten the gun laws for private gun owners.
The authorities are reacting to the latest events: injured in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the shooting of Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov.
The police want to ban the carrying of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act will be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by “attracting the screws”.
An open letter has been published on the Internet, whose authors - representatives of various arms associations - demand the authorities to refrain from "meaningless intensifications".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal lawyer Vasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1.168 thousand crimes were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law for private gun owners will not stop criminals from making use of the black market.
At present, according to the authors, any weapon can be found in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry emphasizes that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons reach the black market through several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts gun orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
“The weapons were stolen by both Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves,” Baranez said.
On the second channel come illegal weapons, the law enforcement are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons stolen both from police armories and directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military stockpiles.
There were frequent explosions at many military camps.
"There is evidence that some cases involved arson to cover up the lack of weapons," the former military official said.
According to Baranez, the weapons manufacturers also make a contribution to the black market.
“Today, there are countless private armament factories that do not withstand international competition and therefore waste their weapons under their hands on the black market, such as in Moscow,” the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a production of its own, sometimes artisanal, as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling," explains the former military personnel.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated what approximately each of the five channels has in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly accessible data on portals on the topic of weapons.
According to investigators, the vast majority of illegal weapons come from the army and the legal protection authorities.
Half of all weapons on the black market are there because of the “guilt of those responsible for their work with weapons,” according to the report.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict zones, 14% are stolen from weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at a weapons store, who doesn’t want to be named, assures that weapons found during illegal excavations haven’t been bought for a long time, as they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get supplies in a weapons warehouse.
An ensign buys a weapon, such as a TT pistol.
The weapon is issued and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros a piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police, of course, know about everything and therefore, if they cannot comply with the plan to expose crimes, periodically carry out control purchases from dealers who offer illegal weapons," the sales consultant adds.
"Like in a luxury shop"
Buyers and sellers find each other most often through acquaintances.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone noticed me and suggested to come to the station "Begovaya", where a person would wait for me, who would take me to a certain place where we could then negotiate the price.
