"The brain can only be outsmarted moderately so far"
The augmented reality theme, popular with fans of modern technologies, has recently been commonly perceived through the lens of special glasses.
First, Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, then in November it was announced that Microsoft had also filed a corresponding patent.
Speaking to the head of the group for interactive 3D technologies at the Microsoft lab in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, it becomes clear, however, that the glasses were only a transit station for the company’s scientists.
It appeals to the possibility of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating virtual open spaces.
- Please briefly describe what research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but we want to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, humanity has largely been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes also touched.
However, we want to look 5-10 years ahead and anticipate the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are an advancement, and nowadays, no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What awaits us in the future?
- Although Kinect has taken the interaction to a physical level, a lot of it still takes place on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output so far not decisive.
We are trying to change that, working on real three-dimensional representation systems based on different technologies, including projections.
We must release the computer world into our physical world and make it more comprehensible.
For this purpose, however, it is necessary that not only the user but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could add virtual objects to the real world much more easily.
And first of all, we should get rid of these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about Voice Control?
It's popular, but isn't it overrated?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, since it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform all bystanders about his actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the field of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and concise, rather than expansive gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed control types, such as gestures and speech.
- Like that?
For example, we'd like to ask you to pass me this can of bubbly?
They say it and at the same time point to it.
- I usually just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does that mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and can’t do at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but this is about a mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work mainly on the development of new types of sensors that make it possible to capture people’s reactions more accurately.
These can be laser sensors, for example, because they offer good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- What are your demands on modern cameras based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or something else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work to do.
It is necessary to take into account not only the resolution along the X and Y axes, but also along the Z axis.
The speed and the number of images per second are also important.
Human movements are extremely dynamic and frankly, the current 30 fps are too low, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor in our lab in Redmond with a controllable processing delay between 1 to 100 milliseconds, with today’s commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between humans and machines.
For my work I needed just such a device, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras could possibly solve the problem...
Or increase the problem, as more calculations would be necessary.
Nice would be a flexible, Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera angles to see how that helps us determine a position three-dimensionally.
- If I remember correctly, unlike Google, Microsoft did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that in terms of applying augmented reality technology in everyday life, glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in the raised hand on the go, but I think this: the most amazing variant would be a "changing" augmented reality, where we could switch from glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and therein lies their strength (private things only you can see), but at the same time also their weakness, because an augmented reality with glasses prevents you from working together with others on virtual objects.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point out: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands feel nothing at all!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
In my lectures, I often speak of augmented reality as the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method at the moment is the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection pad.
She perceives pressure very well!
However, there are also technologies that are actually designed to give the "images in the air" something tangible, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is located produces a feeling that is currently, however, as weak as someone was blowing over the palm of his hand.
There are also ligaments for the wrist that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, also this is a potential direction.
- Did you try to outsmart the brain?
Make it think that it feels what it should feel when it is seeing something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely to make a person who is physically in an enclosed space believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), movable platforms as well as large balls.
So far, the brain is only moderately outsmarted, and there are still many years of hard work ahead of us.
This is what makes working in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: we are only at the beginning of many topics.
