Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global Warming or Collision with Killerasteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth-dwellers on board set out in search of a replacement planet.
In order to save humanity, the important question arises as to how we can reproduce in weightlessness or on the replacement planet?
In my opinion, there are not many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"It's called Mars and Venus," says the research assistant at the Sternberg Institute of Astronomy, Vladimir Surdin.
However, while conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, there is a temperature of 500 degrees on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers first addressed the question of reproduction in space with regard to flora.
Already half a century before, experiments with plants were carried out.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit did not differ in the least from the terrestrial species.
This was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979 quail eggs were sent into space to explore how microgravity affects embryo development.
It develops a completely normal chick.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick has to be able to stand on its feet and start moving," said Vladimir Sychev, head of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems at RAN.
Without solid ground, the chicks overcame wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely blunted.
The chicks did not react to light and sounds.
Four days later, they simply died.
"Two times we let chicks hatch and then stopped the whole thing, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," says Vladimir Sychew about the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last incubator with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be found on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that had already been sent into space in fertilised form.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"This was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research must be continued," notes Vladimir Sychew.
After the landing, the space rats got offspring.
So far, the problem of reproduction directly in space has not been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals torn from their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive instinct.
Unlike animals, humans can do this in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was with Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered the question: Will it survive space flight?
Will she be able to give birth after this flight?
"Finally, no one answered this question," says space veteran Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The child's father, Andrijan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Savizkaja, who was in orbit twice and even worked outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there is still a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts, in which everything went well after long flights and they got healthy offspring.
"The more dangerous it is, even when flying in orbit," concludes cosmonaut Valeri Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet, humanity must look for new paths in biotechnology, radiation protection and the generation of artificial gravity.
The hydro lab in the cosmonaut preparation center is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a suspended state, the cosmonauts gain routine for work in open space.
The water represents weightlessness.
Even if adults find water pleasant, it is a strange environment; but infants perceive water as a natural element.
It is as if the little ichtyanders bear witness that life on land rose from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in the mother’s belly in amniotic fluid for about 9 months, and the fact that it is easier for them to get used to water.
In principle, this is logical, since only 2 weeks pass from birth to the first swim.
“This is too little time to forget something,” says baby swimming teacher Marina Aksenowa.
So while for a newborn child weightlessness is a much more natural state, the woman does not get along without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles recede enormously quickly and thus also the ability to squeeze the child out decreases.
All right, let's get around this through birth-initiating aids.
For example, the birth could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze the child out.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Valery Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the attraction to the earth, the organism cannot form the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put in an exercise suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply lack what is of elementary importance for his life.
"This experiment, which we are conducting together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will result in the birth of a disabled person, a completely inappropriate person," predicts the head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute for Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Igor Pestow.
So far, the birth of children in space is a mere theory.
At some point, however, it becomes a reality when Earth’s inhabitants in their spaceships set off for a distant planet that will be the home for their space-born offspring.
