Public funds, which are managed by us by the districts and municipalities, are subject to the control of the state courts of accounting.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare this without concrete information. Nevertheless, Germany is often referred to as a model in some respects, but one can certainly not say that Germany is better in everything.
Is it because the inspectors are better?
Certainly not, but as I said: I do not like such comparisons very much.
It should also be noted that those countries that set an example for us also have problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have any cooperation with our agency, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what significance did the amendment of the Public Procurement Act have for your authority, do you already feel any impact?
Considering that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had any effect on our examinations.
Since our checks are carried out retrospectively, we have to expect a certain delay here.
We have so far been more affected in the preparatory phase of future controls - for example, we have introduced the new control instrument "Recognition of risks of uneconomicity" and with this almost 14,000 public contracts are examined and analysed - here the changes will of course have an impact, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, etc.
Do you see the adoption of this law rather positively, or is the system burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction and hope that this assumption is confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be adhered to.
Already under the previous rules, the persons subject to an audit are accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to the effect that any non-compliance with the procurement law amounts to a breach of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I do not think that way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have committed a formal error that does not affect actual decision-making.
Such a system only puts the bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out?
First of all, let’s say which path is not effective.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not bother the entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system now prohibited or allowed?
A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then it cannot simply come from the head of the government and obstruct the control office, whose duty is to control compliance with the law, in its activities.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the thing," but he can't say that we're pretending to be nothing.
The Public Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain transactions - and this is also correct for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded due to formal errors alone.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be properly applied - and that is what I think is missing from us.
