<0xC5><0xA0>imon Ornest: We want to gather positive energy at our concerts
What do you think is going to happen in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports that we humans are so eager to jump at.
With our band The Tap Tap, we are more likely to make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also realize a unique project with three concerts towards the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
It’s a nationwide benefit event that we’ve been planning for two years.
For this we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, the end of which is forecast for December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
The day before, i.e. on 20 December, three concerts will take place simultaneously from 21:00 in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be around the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is 12 hours ahead of us in a time zone.
Who did this idea come from?
Originally probably from me, then we developed the idea together with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
Not only do we want to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we once handed this world over to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, t-shirts, bags and key rings against the end of the world, with which people can also support us with their purchase via www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap together with other performers also recorded the so-called anthem against the end of the world with the title "Weltunterfall falt aus".
The anthem is already very popular on YouTube. Will it also be heard at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, provided that everything works out and the end of the world does not take place...
The anthem is to be sung by all performers at all three concerts at the same time.
In addition, the anthems will be broadcast live together in a direct broadcast from Czech Television.
The lyrics of the anthem come from Tom<0xC3><0xA1><0xC5><0xA1> Han<0xC3><0xA1>k, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, Xindl X also sings with...
How did you come to collaborate with both?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many charity events and concerts...
We try to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most people are interested in working with us and enjoy it.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the accessible education center Studeo, where we have been working for six years together with the association Tap in the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute.
The students of the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the editors, we want to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, a separate building is to be built, which we will then move into with this project.
Several groups and performers perform at each concert.
On what criteria did you choose them?
We wanted to put together a program that would appeal to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan B<0xC3><0xA1>rta, The Tap Tap, Mari<0xC3><0xA1>n Bango and Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD> Such<0xC3><0xBD> perform.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "big events" also planned for the future?
In May we perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and for this concert we are preparing an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - when we are in the USA - would like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It’s not as bad as it might seem at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs have to be transported in the luggage compartment. In addition, of course, we have to carry a lot of instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems so far, <0xC4><0x8C>SA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your trips abroad you have a comparison, what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than in Russia, we have seen that everything in the East is still in its beginnings.
Moscow is absolutely not handicapped accessible to Prague, where it is still unusual for someone to be in a wheelchair in the city centre alone.
It is not even self-evident that a wheelchair user can be left in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations there that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still a lot of things we hang on to...
However, it should also be noted that an improvement in the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to be able to move around independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
But it is not exactly common that a larger group of disabled people actively participate in social events there, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in public and accessibility is one thing, but it is only when significant athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come out of our ranks that things really start to change.
So far, these are only isolated cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is very popular at the moment, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a supervisor at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing some intensive work.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone, I founded a music company together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our presenter, L<0xC3><0xA1><0xC4><0x8F>a Angelovi<0xC4><0x8D>, used to say, this has gotten a little out of control (laughs).
But the band has only been known in recent years, or am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us; we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if one does something and this is not visible to the outside, one’s own performance does not exist in a certain sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good proofreaders, high-quality equipment and the like.
Was it your goal to make it this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do things differently.
In show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and accepted only after a long time.
There are few truly unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is, of course, pity; this is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we would have to regret.
They are people who live a full life and can develop, provided they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed in something, it is not only progress for themselves, but for the whole of society.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something well, you must not compromise in many things and also have to demand a certain discipline.
However, I think this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have rehearsals twice a week, have to complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, then enthusiasm quickly goes out for many.
But this is how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them have been there since the beginning, since 1998?
Only one: L<0xC3><0xA1><0xC4><0x8F>a Angelovi<0xC4><0x8D>.
We're an open group. People come and go. You can't stop that.
Who has the will and the desire to participate, is always welcome with us.
