Poland and space.
Last week, Poland became the 20th member of the European Space Agency (ESA) at a meeting of the Council of Ministers, making it the second member country from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s way into space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, although they did not always come across understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, at which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entry to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
<0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, in 1934 for "Entgang zur Kosmonautik".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski’s globally recognized contribution to the development of space travel has been recognized, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the moon’s remote side is named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to start or to brake the draisine.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered missiles.
The research was conducted by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents handed down, it can be seen that the research had progressed to the stage of practical tests.
Research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, a draft of a photoelectric hunting missile by Ing. Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski appeared in the trade press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpedoa powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was terminated from the beginning of the war.
Other articles on space travel appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Agency (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles are devoted to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the establishment of a space company.
At that time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was foreseeable that the exploration of space would have a future.
From its beginnings in 1956, the Polish Space Agency (PTA) sought to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and in fact, the PTA became a full member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA Chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum altitude of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>d<0xC3><0xB3>w Desert, flight tests began with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
The first RM-type rockets were succeeded by the Meteor 1 rocket, which was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the take-off weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor 1A rocket had a transport space with a capacity of 0.4 liters, Meteor 1B over 0.34 liters and Meteor 1C over 0.62 liters.
The maximum altitude of all three types was 37 km.
From 1965 to 1968, the Aeronautical Institute developed the Meteor 2 rocket, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a take-off weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which was followed two years later by the creation of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek.
The repeal of the law on charitable works is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Law on Non-Profit Work.
This decision sparked a lively public debate.
It is certainly interesting to look at the issue from a broader perspective.
The liberal-oriented economic systems in the EU and in the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in permanent conflict with each other.
The reason for this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with rampant financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of labour (wages), there are price tensions.
This term is to be understood as a condition in which the producer tries to compete economically by importing favourable goods, by "undercutting" the competition in order to capture a greater market share and increase its profit.
On a large scale, this means for most companies to move their production abroad or buy cheaply, or to give up their business. The result is high unemployment in countries with comparable high labour costs.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it causes, government spending necessarily increases.
This situation is aggravated by the fact that the gentlemen entrepreneurs are absolutely unwilling to pay their taxes and thereby compensate for the social and economic damage caused by them as a whole.
This situation is well known, so that concrete statistics are superfluous at this point.
The ruthless practice of private capital creates a situation in the individual economies in which governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments deliver their own population to private capital regardless of the social consequences.
This is reflected in particular in changes to applicable laws.
The aim of these measures is to force the own population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially in the wage sector.
This is done, on the one hand, by economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, and, on the other hand, by the curtailment of workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty, as well as ever greater differences between rich and poor.
In Germany, there have been public food delivery points for the poor for several years, who are no longer able to feed themselves through their own work.
The number of people affected is already in the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regularly cases in which employees receive such a low wage that the state must increase their income to the minimum subsistence level.
Such a scandal was also uncovered in the case of aid workers employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all EU southern states will no doubt amount to the same condition in which people are forced to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century) under the pressure of a catastrophic fall in their social level, or to starve for a hunger wage on the margins of society, hoping that eventually private investment capital will flow into the country.
This naturally raises the question of where this capital comes from?
If it comes from another EU country, only poverty migrates from one country to another; or the capital remains the same, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt or Africa in general, the employees work for a fraction of the European wages.
This applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media claim, to the point of exasperation, that the state cannot participate with capital in its own economy, and that the planned economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital insists narrowly on its position that the state must not intervene in the economy.
But then one has to ask oneself whether private capital does not influence or even direct politics and thus the entire state in its own selfish sense.
Here is the clear answer: Yes.
The proof of this is the existence of a virtually all-powerful lobby that is omnipresent in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the field of corruption, mutual preference, legislation in which virtually everything is criminal, but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that, due to a lack of finances, a state ministry commissions private legal companies closely intertwined with industry with the drafting of bills.
These bills will then be passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer emanates from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Obviously, the liberal democracies are rapidly falling into a situation, as Appian describes in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic in the time of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had long been in disrepair, and the offices were occupied by force.
Against bribes, by unlawful extortion of advantages or with stone and sword.
Corruption grew unrestrained, and the people went to the election with votes already bought" ... "People of character did not apply for office, so that the state did not have a consul for eight months as a result of this decline" ... "One really began to talk about that the only medicine in this difficult situation is a strong democracy, and that then a strong man must be elected permanently"...
As it turns out, today’s society, as in ancient times, is based on the reckless preference of one’s own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
Private capital is by its very nature incapable of recognizing and enforcing the advantage for society as a whole.
The result, as it did then, is an unprecedented decadence of the elites who are not in the least interested in deeper reforms.
The cause of the rise of fascism and communism must therefore be sought in the ruthless liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From today’s point of view, the demise of these regimes in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause at which the next round is already looming.
Particularly catastrophic is the fact that today’s elites are in complete ignorance of the potential future loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, the humanitarian and social disasters to which we are already witnessing today, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from older and more recent history.
The repeal of the law on charitable works is not a solution here, at least not a permanent one.
Under pressure from global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue looking for ways to push down the social level of the population.
This trend is systemic.
The only solution is targeted political-social reforms, which increase the state’s participation in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favor of the state.
Israel: Laboratory of Chaos.
"...that nothing arises out of violence, or could ever arise" sings Sting in the song Fragile, whose most important verse in the chorus is "...so that we do not forget how fragile we are" .
“If my sons did not want wars, there would be none,” says the dying Gutele Schnaper, wife of Mayer Amschel Rothschild, in 1849.
After the last wave of violence between Israel and the Gaza Strip, there were, as always, a myriad of reactions.
Some stand behind Israel and argue with its right to self-defense, while others call the Palestinians terrorists; others support the Palestinians, argue with the racism of the Israeli state, with the genocide perpetrated on the Palestinian Arabs, and call the state of Israel terrorist.
I do not want to write at this point about who is guilty and who is the victim in these recurring waves of killing; ultimately, the present inhabitants of Israel, including the self-governing areas, were born into the current political situation and did not experience the beginning of the violence itself.
It is my aim to give readers a behind-the-scenes look at who the 95 years of tension (counting from the Balfour Declaration in November 1917) in the small country in the Middle East are especially useful for.
My thoughts are partly based on accessible historical facts, others are derived from these and emerge from my own understanding of who or which group of people significantly influences the events of modern history.
The history of mankind is first and foremost a history of the struggle for power.
