The film Argo: When it's worst to call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of protesting Islamist students occupied the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the toppled Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the US after the revolution, who had been patronizing his regime for decades.
For the American government, there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to liberate hostages only made things worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days, after negotiations had been brokered by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the US a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy employees managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, succeeded in bringing the refugees out of Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to cover up their true identity – they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff who allegedly visited locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan, developed by exfiltration expert Tony Mendez, also necessitated Hollywood’s cooperation.
For the camouflage to be credible, articles about this film project appeared in trade journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussars piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels alternate in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no major differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which are ironic and slightly exaggerated.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, in the hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable new start to his career with this film.
A ridiculed actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor, he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the thriller No Child's Play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller City Without Mercy (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film not set in the director’s native Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that set this director’s previous films apart from the standard of Hollywood.
Affleck, however, also proves this sense in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the opening sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, and yet conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when history moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team also achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (the false film staff at a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story actually does not offer many exciting scenes in the filmic sense.
However, he works quite successfully with the few, sometimes helping the reality somewhat - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a phone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem somewhat contrived).
The weakness of Argo is its all-too-wide spread, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters would have earned more space, and thus they are far from alone in the film.
As a result, Affleck’s film loses some traction, and it is a film that can be followed with a certain amount of interest, while at the same time gauging the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70s.
However, it is difficult to arouse enthusiasm.
However, it is sufficient as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive to this day in a certain way and as proof of how exaggerated the ideas of the all-powerful and all-knowing secret services are.
