Controversial EU regulations include the mandatory addition of bioethanol to fuels, which in turn is harmful to nature, the ban on reliable mercury thermometers simply because they contain a relatively small amount of this dangerous substance, and the directive on the size of chicken cages, which made eggs much more expensive this year.
In the past, criticism also reaped the de facto ban on the use of the term "butter spread" or the ban on the sale of conventional light bulbs.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU apparatus often decides under the pressure of this or that lobby from trade and industry, whose demands in Brussels are usually represented by one or more member countries (for example, the Czech Republic is currently trying to enforce the demands of Czech banks with a veto threat).
Lobbying interests were also behind the fact that bananas of the highest commercial class in the EU must be at least 14 cm long and must not have a "curvature anomaly".
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was merely harmonising the inconsistent national standards that would hinder trade.
The standards on fruit and vegetables have already been softened by the EU against the resistance of some countries with the indication that the previous directives would lead to a waste of food.
