The MVRDV architects prove that the real adventures are not just in the head - using the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there is something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by at the roadside.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician in a nearby large company, says: "Yes, it's beautiful, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
All have internet, iPad and e-books.
No one goes to one of these old-style libraries voluntarily today, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy city that hardly needs a visit at the gates of Rotterdam, is a curious record holder.
The 80,000-strong community has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, it was decided a few years ago to contribute to general education and to recreate the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro notes as nicely painted reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master statistics: a library had to come here!
Winy Maas from the Rotterdam architecture firm MVRDV, master of the foolhardy bar charts and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with familiar composure and appeared for the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the jury looked around in amazement and shrugged its shoulders, the cheeky Maas piled his exquisite souvenirs in size to a pyramid and finished his actionist-backed speech with the words: "Dear Stadtgemeinde!"
So this is it, my proposal for the Book Mountain of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Book Mountain!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain has been raised.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and townhouses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project has also been nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, the faceless small-town retorts, which up to now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian street and a stunnedly ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory, to enrich a piece of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The long road to the book
The first impression: book Eldorado under cheese bell.
Although there is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, the true joys of space and reading are revealed when climbing the topography on foot.
The all-glass interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lamps speak the language of a public city square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and football-playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
“Usually, the bookshelves are placed along the facade, and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and turned the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the Buchenberg is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, internet library, chess club, environmental center and building technology center.
A special pleasure are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall cladding, sometimes parapet, sometimes railings.
Optics, haptics and smell are foreign.
Even die-hard architects and civil engineers shake their heads at the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, at the request of the standard.
And so we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture one day in a Friesland farm.
For many years, a millimetre-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root pad in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
This is cheap and time efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ready for bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece was pressed - for the first time in these quantities - into four-centimeter-thick plates.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material that smells like a new car and a sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500 meter long hike, the Literature Café not only offers a fantastic view of the city, but also rewards you with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide an atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literature mountains.
Donations for the New Soul
“You wouldn’t believe it, but this house is a showcase project in terms of ecology, despite the many glass surfaces,” says Trouborst.
It is heated and cooled with geothermal heat.
Although the Buchenberg is under a glass lintel, the sun shines only briefly inside on sunny days.
The wide wooden glue binders, which are transverse to the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, serve as shading and absorb a large part of the sunlight.
The room climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even describes Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "long overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal holdings.
For the time being, this is intended to fill the optical gaps in the not yet fully equipped library - currently 70,000 pieces.
The concept has taken off.
The shelves are filled to the top.
“Nothing is worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for decoration.
In this way, MVRDV has succeeded in achieving the supreme discipline that is called the Identity Foundation in technical jargon.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
