Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had first signaled that it would vote against the request for an observer status of the Palestinians at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
What's up?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany has to be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don’t think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence – but not be too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was eventually enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is changing its foreign policy away from a policy managed by the US, so to speak, to a German foreign policy.
To make matters worse, Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans, therefore, find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
