‘Brand Protection’ in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-renowned brand, as is Polo Ralph Lauren.
What is Armani Polo?
This is a name that is officially registered in China, but has nothing to do with the original companies.
Yet it enjoys protection as long as the actual namesakes do not complain.
And even then, it is not clear if they are right.
“It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” says Thomas Pattloch, an attorney at Taylor Wessing, a law firm specializing in property rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case lands on my desk.
A few additional letters are enough for the imitators to be allowed to register their trademarks.
So Gucci becomes simply Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada you let Prada-Kny enter.
German companies are also legally copied in this way, such as the sporting goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a folder with registrations of the Trademark Office in Beijing.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company had the trademark Zegna DF Puma protected, an art name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
It is well known that the Chinese are world champions in copying and in injuring intellectual property.
In the big cities, there are multi-storey department stores that sell almost exclusively counterfeits.
However, Pattloch’s cases are different: on behalf of his clients, he opposes the fact that Chinese companies are officially granted the right by the Trademark Office to use a designation that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Mingpai", a passenger brand.
The word is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
This means women who fish for rich men.
The Chinese authorities are not aware of any guilt
"This is business-damaging, you have to fight it," Pattloch demands.
"The brand is watered down, the uniqueness disappears, the image damage is enormous."
The financial failures and the legal costs of the affected industries are in the millions, especially for expensive flagship products.
According to the market research company CLSA, China is the third largest market for luxury goods and the fastest growing, with a volume of 15 billion euros per year.
However, deletions of dubious entries in the trademark register are difficult to reach and go into the money.
The procedure can take up to nine years, with an uncertain outcome.
Pattloch reports on cases in which the court dismissed complaints because, after the long duration, the disputed name had become a "market reality".
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he even has to pay the plagiarist money because he violated his trademark in China, says Pattloch.
Sometimes the law of the jungle prevails here.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle with the construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that recently took over the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
The Chinese are therefore still allowed to use an emblem that resembles the Mercedes star.
The Volvo buyer Geely originally used a blue and white logo reminiscent of BMW; the dispute was settled, Geely had to change it.
The fashion manufacturer Lacoste lost in China against imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore, who made the famous crocodile look the other way.
The Chinese authorities are not aware of any guilt.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing admits that there were shortages there in 2010 due to insufficient personnel and space.
In the past year, however, people have returned from the “emergency situation in the workflow to normality”.
For example, the number of unprocessed opposition proceedings had fallen by 22 percent.
Nearly 57,000 such cases have been closed, 75 percent more than in the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 appeals are still awaiting execution in the office.
Dealing with it costs a lot
As so often in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
This is a record and means that China is leading the list of new applications around the world for the tenth time in a row, the authority says.
This also applies to the stock of all valid trademarks, a total of 5.5 million pieces.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan in fees were collected.
Simplified, this means that each registration costs an average of 1280 yuan or 160 euros.
To tackle this costs a lot, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting against a Chinese plagiarist.
Although the Germans were able to achieve that its illegal manufacture of imitated motor vehicle parts was excavated.
However, the copycat continued to secure Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
They themselves have failed to do so, as family names could not be protected in Germany, says Hanno Wentzler, Chairman of the Board of Management of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office rejected the objection of the Munich authorities.
In the next two instances, Freudenberg got right, but the opponent continues to fight to this day.
You have to be hellishly careful
The matter is now before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident of bringing the matter to a good conclusion and praises the professionalism of the courts.
But he also says, “The procedure is extremely time-consuming and takes a lot of time, money and nerves.”
The internal costs could hardly be quantified, the company archive even had to look through 100-year-old files to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg offered the other side a "high six-digit euro amount" for settlement in vain.
“You can see how much this is worth to us,” Wentzler says.
The dangers in the Far East are even threatening to sweep back to Europe.
That’s when impersonators secure unprotected marks.
For example, a Chinese manufacturer in Germany wanted to register the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather.
The Group has long since abandoned this business area, but was nevertheless able to avert registration.
“You have to be careful,” Wentzler says.
Both he and the lawyer Pattloch advise German companies to be very careful when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark rights, rather the foreigners should "apply everything that is somehow worthy of protection, also in China," as Wentzler says.
This can be much more expensive than registration.
In fact, if Freudenberg was subject to his trademark drama in the last act, then you would probably have to pay the other side royalties for his own name, explains Wentzler.
Or we will be forced out of the market in the segment in question.
