Facts about Sexually Transmitted Infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STI includes syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
Common viral STIs are HIV, human pappilomaviruses, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Lice and scabies belong to the parasitic STI.
Who are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and tripper are especially common in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five of all reported cases of syphilis in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (fungus), trippers, and human pappilomaviruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults in Germany is comparatively low - nevertheless: This group accounts for around 20 percent of new HIV infections.
Among adolescents, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In this country, human pappilomaviruses are also common in adolescents.
How has the number of infections developed?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are reported.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1697 in 2001 to 3698 in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
That’s about a tenth less than the year before.
What symptoms indicate an STD?
The infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort during urination, discharge, lower abdominal pain as well as blisters or warts.
However, they often do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore go unnoticed.
How to protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not provide 100% protection.
In some cases, pathogens from sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through smear infections and close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially for frequently changing sex partners.
Early diagnosed, most STI can be cured and late consequences avoided.
