His speech was addressed to the whole people, but above all to the Christian Copts, the liberals, enlightened Muslims and seculars.
Because all of them, so far hopelessly divided in a confused opposition, are afraid.
Fear of a state of God on the Nile by the graces of the powerful Muslim Brotherhood.
He said, almost apologetically, that he had temporarily curtailed the powers of the Constitutional Court and expanded his powers “to save the revolution.”
But what the 61-year-old engineer, who holds a doctorate from the American University of Southern California, really wants to save, the Egyptians are concerned about, the world is not quite clear.
Should the judiciary be abolished?
In fact, the 234 articles whipped through by the Islamist-dominated 100-member Constituent Assembly in a nocturnal, 15-hour parforce ride are partly of concern.
As in previous constitutions, the draft also states that the jurisprudence is based on the "principles of Islamic law".
But what do we mean by "principles"?
This was and is a matter of interpretation and it is to be feared that the Islamists will use the spongy formulation and the accompanying legal scope for a stricter interpretation of Sharia law.
This is at least suggested by a newly added article: Al-Ashar University, the country’s most important Islamic institution, must be consulted on all matters relating to Sharia law, with great significance in all Sunni Islam.
This does not have to be, but it can mean that the clergy supervise the legislation, which would de facto result in the disenfranchisement of the judiciary.
Much of the draft constitution is a matter of interpretation
Also problematic: Civilian military jurisdiction should continue to be maintained.
During Mubarak's reign, these courts were used to suppress oppositionists.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were in military custody.
According to the draft, the state should also “protect the true essence of the Egyptian family and promote its morality and values.”
This is legally so vaguely worded that state institutions could even control the content of film art and literature with the help of this article.
In plain language, this means nothing more than censorship.
By the way, no article explicitly stipulates equality between men and women.
For this, another forbids insulting or slandering the Prophet Muhammad and his Messengers.
But what an insult is and how it should be punished remains unclear.
Equally dubious seems the formulation that "insulting people" is forbidden.
Is a caricature of the president enough or a joke at the expense of a legal scholar?
A matter of interpretation, as is the case with so much in the draft, which Morsi has signed and which, in his words, will be presented to the Egyptians "very soon" for a referendum.
“The revolution has returned.”
The opposition has been forming for weeks against the superiority of the Islamists.
Tens of thousands gathered in unusual concord on Friday night in Cairo’s Tahrir Square, vowing to bring down the Charter before it can enter into force.
“The revolution has returned and we will win,” said Hamdin Sabbahi, third-placed in the presidential election.
Nobel Peace Prize laureate and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El-Baradei said the draft constitution “belongs to the garbage mountain of history.”
Via short message service Twitter, he accused the followers of Morsi, to want to lead a "coup against democracy".
“If he calls the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him,” said opposition leader Jasser Said.
"We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers has not yet been purged," Egyptian media quoted Chaled Ali as saying.
And several judges announced that they did not want to monitor the referendum, which would invalidate it.
"The Koran is our Constitution"
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, for its part, blew to the counter-demonstration, but as a precaution not in Tahrir Square, but after a mass prayer on the other bank of the Nile in front of Cairo University.
Many veiled women and followers of the Salafists took part and shouted, “The people demand the application of God’s law.”
They demanded of Morsi: "Cleanse the land!" and asserted: "The Koran is our constitution."
A battle for sovereignty over the symbolic Tahrir Square, where everything began, would have evoked conditions similar to civil war.
Morsi’s supporters obviously didn’t want to risk that.
The Muslim Brotherhood said both opponents of the draft constitution and supporters had spoken out loud and clear.
Now is the time to let the people at the ballot box decide in which direction the country should go.
A majority for the draft of the Islamists is considered safe.
"The word human rights does not even occur"
Hafez Abu Saeda is furious about this forced constitutional process, which should have gone until February and involved all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were in prison or on trial under Mubarak.
Not because he would share their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible to him.
For this he was beaten, condemned, imprisoned.
“And now the word human rights is not even in the new constitution,” he laments in an interview with the “Welt am Sonntag”.
Morsi’s extension of power to all three powers in the state caused the lawyer to resign.
These measures are blatant violations of democratic rules and will lead Egypt into a new dictatorship.
“Instead of strengthening civil society, the president de facto overrules it,” Saeda laments.
But without civil society organisations, a democracy could not work.
Saeda feels left alone, also by the international community, which looks at the ideological battle of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and suspense.
This could be revenge.
A protester on the Tahrir warns: "You give birth to a monster that you can no longer control."
Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most foul-smelling fish in the world?
Norway’s five million inhabitants enjoy one of the highest standards of living – not only in Europe, but around the world.
Could the country’s secret of success have anything to do with the local appetite for rather foul-smelling fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of dirty, wet sportswear.
And leave them there for a week.
It’s about the nose-numbing smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway’s great delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There’s snow here, spectacular scenery – and that stubborn smell in the air that just doesn’t want to disappear.
Rakfisk is trout sprinkled with salt, which - depending on how stinky you would like your fish to be - is fermented in water for up to a year.
When the darkness comes over the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes, which is dedicated to this, well, really very impressive specialty.
"You eat it raw and then rinse it down with a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works at the local fire station, but also hosts the festival as a so-called "Rakfisk general".
Around us, people eat small fish cubes and drink large amounts of alcohol.
“Some people like the Aquavit more than the Rakfisk,” says Havard.
The spirit can supplant the smell.
I'll have a few bites.
If you avoid bringing the rakfisk close to your nose, it is not bad - like sushi, which has a fairly long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a very different, much poorer Norwegian era, when there were no cooling options and fish was soaked in airtight saltwater barrels in autumn.
In the deepest winter, it was then taken out after long fermentation and, no doubt with the help of alcohol-steamed senses, consumed.
A generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and mainly emigrated to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly – more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labor market, high wages and comprehensive health care.
Even from Sweden, the old rival, who was much richer than Norway not so long ago, immigrants are pouring in.
Rakfisk is considered to be something important - an essential, though strictly smelly, part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the more expensive dishes that can be bought here.
But actually everything is expensive here - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs a proud 10 euros.
Norway doesn’t make it into the world press often, and most people don’t seem to mind that.
Here you still hate to call Anders Breivik by his name - the racist right-wing extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, it only refers to the “July 22 incident.”
Norwegians have a hard time accepting that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal killings.
Since the early 1970s, Norway has been responsible for the growth of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, who distributes round trays with mature rakfish and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blonde hair and piercing blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a prudent people.
Your English, like most people here, is flawless.
We are not very boastful, we do not like boasting.
Norway has handled its oil wealth very carefully – a large part of the industry’s earnings is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When, in the years leading up to the Great Depression, everyone was throwing money around that they didn’t even have, Norway kept its wallet tightly locked.
“As long as we can ski in the winter and go hiking in the summer, we’re happy,” says Anna.
"And, of course, eat rakfisk," she adds with carefree laughter.
I’m standing in the snow and I’m standing up for another dish – I’ve had enough of Rakfisk.
A moose burger is definitely something else. The juicy meat feeds me.
But in the evening, the smelt fish is again on the menu.
The hotel I stay at is one of several venues that organize a rakfisk dinner where guests can vote for the best – or perhaps the most olfactory – fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a fly-clad showmaster surrounded by plates with rakfisk.
The show is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
"Here's our points, Havard".
You clap and laugh.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by aquavit.
But maybe it is the harsh haze of the whole fish.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces a difficult start
As Mexico’s future president, Enrique Pena Nieto, prepares to take office, BBC’s Will Grant analyses the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad.
Even on better days, this is a constantly clogged city, but on Monday a ring of steel was built, blocking several important traffic routes into the capital and causing chaos on the streets.
The goal, however, was not to disrupt commuters on the way to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential tie and take over the leadership of the nation.
He faces a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has proved economically successful, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
“My administration is deeply committed to reducing violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama at the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy to achieve this goal.
Prior to joining the U.S. government, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, sprawling part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A direct man
In the remote town of Valle del Bravo, for example, people like to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute to it the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto built and which represent a great improvement over the brittle, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques bearing his name also hang outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect him to make real and lasting changes," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the Pena Nietos party, the PRI.
In particular, when it comes to security and the economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so desperately needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high expectations for Enrique Pena Nieto.
The accusations of the opposition, the new president is lacking in substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
Tucked away under highway overpasses, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of a crucial urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was called in to fight drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
In a patch of fallow land near a large landfill, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left behind in the past two years alone.
During the reign of Governor Pena Nieto, more than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico – a statistic that surpasses even that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murders of innocent women.
The critics of Pena Nieto believe that he at least did not adequately address the problem of women’s murder during his term in office.
But in the worst case, his government has closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the rundown neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears when she shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her partner.
“When I arrived at her house, it seemed as if her body had been washed,” recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and the body rigidity had already set in.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down at us from the wall, next to a cross bearing a single word: justice.
But this, according to the family, has been denied to her until now.
The authorities have treated me as if I were a chatterbox, a troublemaker, a troublemaker.
They want you to just accept their judgment and keep your mouth shut.
“But that’s not possible if there were so many form errors and omissions,” she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidential bond on Saturday, he also assumes a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crime over the past six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this issue during his term in office.
“I hope, as president, he is as he was as governor,” said PRI congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But this is precisely what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza are most afraid of.
Attorney General Says Bradley Manning Didn't Complain About Abuse
Prosecutors disagree with Bradley Manning's allegations that he was abused in prison
The hearing focuses on Manning’s time in military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks to dismiss the indictment on the basis of harsh conditions of detention
The U.S. Army’s private is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
Prosecutors on Friday tried to establish that Army Libertarian Bradley Manning — indicted for the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history — missed several opportunities to complain about the abuse he allegedly suffered in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein explained that documents on weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning’s nine-month term in Quantico, Virginia, did not raise any complaints about his treatment.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to dismiss the charge - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard time in prison - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his time in Iraq.
The material was then published on the Internet by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
In Friday’s hearing, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officials had filled out after their meetings with Manning during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he had been incarcerated under increased detention conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein questioned him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards to be “excellent” and the treatment by the facility overall to be “very professional.”
The forms, Fein said, contained no complaints of abuse, even though officials had directly questioned Manning about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they would deal with them, but they had not been logged.
“They wrote ‘no problems’ (after discussing the concerns), and that didn’t necessarily mean I didn’t say anything at all,” Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal ideation he had mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during this meeting was to downgrade his observation status to “prevention of injury.”
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status — which is one level below the suicide risk — to his and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well, and get rid of the observational status for injury prevention (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life in my view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Naval Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and had once become unconscious due to the heat.
Not being able to know what was going on with him or in the outside world was a burden.
“My world shrank at Camp Arafjon, on this cage together,” Manning said.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell—at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours—and without company.
They only allowed him a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he had tried to keep moving because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or even to lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that entered his cell from the outside.
If he had turned around at night and guards could no longer see his face, they would have woken him up so that he would turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned an accusation he had made in his statement on Thursday — for example, he had to sleep naked in his Quantico cell one night and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to wrap himself in his blanket during this count.
At the interview on Friday, Manning said he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket he could have used to cover himself with, but admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning testified that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night and had previously tried to show an official that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the official that he could have used the waistband of his underpants or flip-flops to hurt himself, but did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least consider his detention experiences and drastically reduce his detention if he is convicted at his trial in the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has stated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser offenses, while other charges that are considered too extreme will be challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend, and the public prosecutor's office is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon maintains its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the provisions that apply to all detainees held under the highest security precautions at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, unlawful disclosure of intelligence on the Internet, the transmission of national defense information, and the theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all charges, he faces a life sentence.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame the emigrants - they remind them of hard times, he says
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at passport control when perplexity spread within me.
Signs refer to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure of what to go to.
I grew up in central California and have been called "Mexican" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Iren" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italians".
Later, I decided to go for "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather’s home, there was no need for hyphens or hyphens.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in that language at both ends of an interview.
But I don’t have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I don’t get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and stood in line for extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all the topics that one would expect when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans today are just as likely to stay in Mexico rather than immigrate to the United States.
He wants to ally himself with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue Mexico’s war on the drug cartels, even if he did not give any details about it.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought on the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the leadership of the country under held gun to give them more than half of their territory.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not minutes, memories of this event are not to be missed.
So as soon as a U.S. government official makes even the mildest criticism of Mexico, one hears complaints - in the Mexican press and among the country's elites - about how the Americans are pressuring the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma go on the path of war.
And yet, Mexico’s biggest challenge lies in the truth in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There is more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican descent live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio is because at one point in our family tree, a person — perhaps a parent or grandparent — was offered no chance in Mexico and migrated north.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty is to them.
Not Mexico.
And while we may now be living the American dream, attending good schools and getting good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream that we are living – not the Mexican one.
Our identity may be blurred at times, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And then we wouldn’t see ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain now—with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that tensions exist between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are — and Mexican Americans resent them for doing so.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel they belong neither to one country nor to another.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but is not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
How I should learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: Some Mexican leaders and parts of the educated middle class want to resume their connections to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional "ambassadors" for Mexico, who represent their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues about how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties to Mexico.
Well, now.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unfair distribution of income, rampant corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through this alone, amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet willing to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans harbor resentment for how their family members were treated not so long ago.
- Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old Battles, New Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected cornerstone for peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to nip such hope in the bud.
Amid the usual blames, countless buildings have been laid in ruins, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed – and for the first time rockets have been fired from Gaza near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But while Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this turmoil.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the fatal stalemate could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism in view of the current situation seems to be anything but appropriate.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November continues, this week’s fighting has strengthened the hard-boiled on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, even though its group itself suffered great losses.
Although several Hamas leaders are killed and the 1.7 million residents of the Gaza Strip are crammed into one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to annihilate Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders may come to the conclusion that they have time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power once considered Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has sided with Hamas – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Cheering Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, where the militant Hezbollah has power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist character could face the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt – by far the most populous and most important Arab country – on Israel’s southern flank has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his overthrow in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is intertwined with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could turn out to be an actor that cannot even be pushed out by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, allow an opposite conclusion to be drawn.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, "Iron Dome", has proved its worth and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep more peacefully.
From a diplomatic point of view, the United States remains steadfast in its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalation of violence.
Israel has been doing well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers, not least thanks to the blockades that extend into the West Bank and thus into the bulk of any Palestinian state, which protect Jewish settlements, which were declared to be in violation of international law but are still being expanded.
Netanyahu is doing well and his Likud party has allied with an even more militant group in the run-up to the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why coddle these insidious Palestinians and leave them a state of their own?
If they actually had control of the West Bank, wouldn’t they be firing rockets just like their fellow Gazans?
No, it is better to keep them behind the wall in check and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will be able to prevail, but the Arab Spring could put a stop to them.
Even if the Islamists, now in power in Egypt and other countries, have little to do with Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties at home.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments in the restoration of their economy.
That pragmatic President Morsi teamed up with Barack Obama to reach a ceasefire could be a promising sign – and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think longer-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking tentative steps toward democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination – a powder keg that will undoubtedly one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Suppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to push Hamas back in the Gaza Strip will increasingly take its diplomatic toll over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside
The correct answer is that represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, most of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states where Israel cedes territories for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt, together with Turkey and Qatar, must now stop arms shipments to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by territorial exchanges and a common Jerusalem.
Foreign Arab nations should also persuade Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the upcoming application for UN observer status.
Obama must also do his part to get Israel to negotiate.
During his first term in office, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems as if he is equally averse to participation.
But that is an unfortunate, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a major interest in a stable Middle East.
And that includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian Uniform Cigarette Packaging Laws Enter Into Force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging laws have come into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colours with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with dramatic images showing sick body parts and infants and children suffering from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packs in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small letters, will be from next Saturday.
This means that Australia is introducing the strictest regulations for tobacco packaging in the world.
The Australian government wants to discourage young people from smoking by removing the glamorous image of tobacco use.
Studies have shown that people who haven’t started smoking at the age of 26 are 99% likely not to start smoking after that.
"You can already see in children at a young age that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," says Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have only a minor impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would favour the black market trade, which would lead to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
“The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences,” says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer far larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the intolerable packaging has increased enormously since the British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco companies failed two months ago at the Supreme Australian Court with their challenge to the laws.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale businesses and is awaiting new inventory.
This is a good deal for us.
According to experts, the catch in the popularity of social media lies with exactly the population group to which the plan is aimed.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, banned them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most retailers to stop interpreting cigarettes in stores. Now tobacco advertising has switched to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned internet advertising by local businesses and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
“Anyone who markets tobacco and only has a small area left to promote their products can’t get around the internet,” says Becky Freeman, a healthcare researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook, Freeman has seen a surge in testimonials on brands written by “quite normal people.”
One has to ask oneself the question: Is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that they even record a video for it - or does a marketing agency have to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says that instead of marketing, the industry is focused on dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations – those countries complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions, even though none of the countries engage in greater trade with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has held talks with other countries that are considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to issue photographic warnings in 2001.
Meanwhile, these have been expanded to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are reluctant.
The pictures do not affect me.
I just ignore them.
"You just take a dump and put the box away," says Victor El Hage when buying a cigarette box, on which a photo with a mouth tumor is printed.
Honestly, there's only one reason I'd stop, and that's my little girl.
James Yu, operator of the tobacco trade “King of the Pack” in downtown Sydney, says the uniform packaging has made it difficult to replenish its shelves.
“It used to take me an hour to sort a delivery, now I need four,” Yu says.
"The government should have just banned cigarettes completely - then we would have said okay, that's it, we're closing," he adds visibly enraged.
In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored.
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane failed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had plenty of time to think about boredom.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is pretty upsetting — even when books, magazines, and iPhones (and, of course, tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts are citing boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it’s okay for us — and our children — to get bored on occasion.
This forces the brain to get lost in interesting thought processes, which may encourage creativity.
And because most of us these days are almost constantly staring at one or the other screen, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yeah, yeah.
And no.
I'll come back to that.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively recent phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011) doesn't see it that way.
“In fact, boredom has a very long history,” he says.
Pompeii’s house walls are decorated with Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of “wanting to perform a satisfying activity but not being able to do it.”
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy but wants to be.
In the case of apathy, on the other hand, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is a “disruption of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is only passing slowly.”
Boredom can almost sound like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored individuals see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed individuals see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored, even if we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", which appeared in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a volume on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups listened to a loud TV program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content, others listened to it at low volume so that it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television reported feeling more boredom than the other two groups – they had trouble concentrating, couldn’t find a reason for it, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
When trying to focus on a difficult or strenuous task, disrupting attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
If, on the other hand, you are engaged in a monotonous activity - "like searching for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help you not to feel bored."
In fact, he says, we now know that fidgeting and scribbling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually combat it by keeping people more physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to bounce around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," said Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my delayed flight, a booming speaker, a particularly tiring movie.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers in the 1980s developed a "scale of long-female susceptibility."
On the scale are statements such as "Many things I have to do are repetitive and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys get bored more often than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida - particularly when it comes to the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty tight-knit bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents with a pager seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32% of adolescents were bored at school and doing homework, while 23% reported being bored when they were not in school.
However, only 3% of parents reported feeling bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn’t know whether the percentages have risen or fallen in terms of boredom.
However, he is certain that "youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have a major impact on their everyday lives.
So back to my original question: is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and fall into gambling or drugs to relieve them - studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors are investigating the relationship between boredom and creativity. This is the opinion of Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the topic for more than two decades.
“With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do best.
If you’re bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you’ll be happy.
But while television can bring happiness in the short term, it will disappear in the long run.
So if you give your bored child an iPad, you can take it away from boredom, but it has not taught them to entertain or control themselves, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds, “Self-control transfers from one situation to another.”
The child not only learns to converse, but also gets more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we be too critical of them.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant activity and technology rush.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“It sounds like we need to be bored more often, but boredom is the agonizing, relentless desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
He believes that people are really just looking for a way to shut down and relax.
“In an environment where we’re constantly overstimulated, it’s hard to keep busy once the noise has stopped.”
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
19-year-old community college student and soccer player Anthony Orozco is facing trial in southeastern Colorado for a misdemeanor that will soon be legal in that state: owning a few marijuana chunks and a pipe he used to smoke them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were traveling by car in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was subpoenaed for possession of drugs and drug paraphernalia — cavalier offenses, each with a $100 fine — and given a court date.
"We are treated like criminals," Orozco said.
But is he also one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state’s decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for personal use, the answer to hundreds of minor drug offenses depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of marijuana-related misdemeanours are already being dropped here and in the state of Washington, which approved similar measures.
Police agencies will no longer prosecute adults over the age of 21 for small-scale possession, which is permitted by law as soon as the new laws come into force in the next few weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado’s more conservative districts have announced they will pursue existing marijuana offenses and are still quoting people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, are voting to block new, state-licensed marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
“This situation is evolving so fast that I don’t even know what’s going to happen next,” said Daniel J. Oates, chief of police in Aurora, just east of Denver.
Regulators in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - and have a deadline until December 1, 2013.
In Washington, it is believed that Colorado is definitely ahead of most states when it comes to regulating marijuana, where the drug was first legalized for medical purposes and then for personal use.
“Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well-suited for orientation,” said Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the liquor regulator in Washington State.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve in the sense of a rough guide.
"We don't have a real precedent that we can follow," he adds.
The Washington law, called I-502, comes into force on December 6, and thus also forms the endpoint of a gray area, in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but the possession is legalized.
And unpleasant practical questions need to be clarified during this time - such as how the government's requirement of "adequate access" to licensed marijuana should be agreed with the ban on cannabis shops within 300 meters around schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
“Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, particularly in the metropolitan area of Seattle,” said Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent an email to his staff in Aurora stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses in persons over 21 years of age, and that police would not seek criminal charges for these offenses “from now on.”
Chief Oates added that the police will continue to enforce city regulations on medical marijuana growers and will continue to persecute drug traffickers.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck takes a stricter view.
After the vote, he said his agency would continue to pursue cases of marijuana possession, mainly to get consumers to withdraw.
Currently, 119 people have to answer for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana in court, although many have also been charged with other offenses.
“Our agency has a duty to prosecute violations that were crimes at the time,” Buck said in a statement.
Reactions are ambivalent even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county’s largest city, no longer report adults for possession of small amounts.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all pending possession proceedings.
“I don’t think I’m wasting my time enforcing the law until it changes,” he says.
Although 55% of voters in Colorado supported the measure, it was clear from the start that it would not be easy to reconcile personal marijuana use with the complexities of government and the legal system.
And the conflicting reactions across the state fostered a deep-seated rift among local officials over the great green experiment.
District attorneys are a “cultural barrier,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents defendants on trial for marijuana offenses and acts as a spokesman for the national marijuana law reform organization on the ground.
“They’ve spent so much of their lives prosecuting people for not being able to accept legalization,” he says.
As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana such as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are being treated as national model cases for drug legalization.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an era of legal sales, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government, which wants to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at the federal level as a crime.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will give in.
Despite several sensational arrests of consumers and sellers of medical marijuana, the federal government has largely allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration, believes that while criminal investigators are unlikely to enter doors to confiscate smaller amounts of the drugs, they are likely to resist tolerating legal, state-regulated marijuana deals under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado aren’t even waiting for federal agencies to act.
Even before Election Day, some local councils approved moratoriums on new marijuana businesses, though these could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city to the west, decided on a six-month ban, which is expected to be passed next week.
"We don't want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at the federal level," said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our community voted against this amendment.
We focus on what the community has chosen, not on what the state has chosen.
There are still many questions to be answered.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied out of Oxford because I'm Tory
Not only university students of today are being attacked for their views
It has always been my biggest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended the university that I once thought was the greatest temple of knowledge in the world, a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization - free thought and tolerance.
But within two weeks of moving into Worscester College at the end of the 1980s - where I had planned to study history - I had packed my bags again and thus caused the first scandal of my life.
My father broke down in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I left because I had a problem with fellow students having sex in the neighboring room.
Author A. N. Wilson mischievously declared that I had left university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
But the truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had only been harassed for one reason - one reason that seemed all the more narrow-minded and cruel in this alleged cradle of enlightenment: my late father Woodrow Wyatt had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to current reports, a new generation of moderate-right students is suffering from similar persecution.
The organized and rising hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week called for the same equality protection that benefits gay, disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College’s Junior Common Room (JCR) say they are “often actively isolated, personally attacked, and declared undesirable” because of their political views.
They demand a place on their college’s equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Their situation was exacerbated by a recent documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", portraying Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
Among others, it showed graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the conservative student association of the University of Oxford, who drove in a Rolls-Royce and flaunted with a silver suit and silver-studded walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are considered “scapegoats for introducing higher tuition fees.”
Twenty-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the University of Nottingham’s conservative student union, said in a Sunday paper: “There is a growing tendency to the left in universities.
“People think we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know each other.”
Samuel Roberts, 21 and history student in Corpus Christi, who initiated the application for greater protection, believes such a climate is “unpleasant.” 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, president-elect of the Oxford Conservative Student Association, says she has observed a growing rejection among JCR members of students of the moderate right.
“This poses a threat to intellectual discourse and the well-being of members,” she says.
In my first few weeks in Oxford, I was part of such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old I arrived in September 1986.
Hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university voted not to award an honorary degree to Margaret Thatcher - a former student - due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have even alarmed Stalinists.
In the first few days of the freshman week, when new students got to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of what would happen in the future.
I found that the tutors not only tolerated the taunting of Tory students, but even enjoyed participating.
Political issues such as the miners’ strike, privatisation and the government’s rejection of sanctions against South Africa’s apartheid regime made their way into the tutorial’s wood-paneled rooms.
At my first of these events, I was supposed to translate 18th-century French texts into English, and I was not prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I tripped over it.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and quite spiteful.
“Do Thatcher followers refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?” he asked.
The other students giggled.
In my eyes there were tears.
“I suggest they take a few French lessons in your spare time — so if you’re not too preoccupied with your social activities,” Pitt growled.
I returned to my room with my head hanging.
That night, I was sitting alone at dinner in college when someone lightly tapped me on the shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the Conservative Student Association.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is as it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory will be harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be worse for you.
Most Tory freshmen pretend to be Labour Party supporters.
In a local pub, I later tried to pretend.
I insisted that I disagreed with Mrs. Thatcher on all points.
This trick should prove unsuccessful.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and economics who had ironically attended Eton College, which is considered conservative, said to me, “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.”
You're dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
“How do Tories have sex?” someone asked me.
They beat each other, right?
I felt like homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever be able to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that lay before me stretched before my mind’s eye to a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only tutor who openly identified himself as Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history, who was based in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also because he had advised Thatcher on foreign policy and written speeches for her.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty and rejected it for its Marxist-determinist historical perspective.
In 1997, he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You’re not going to be happy here,” he told me.
I began to commute between Oxford and my parents’ house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why I did it.
He seemed incredulous.
During his time in the forties, all political views were accepted.
“But it’s the best place in the world,” he said softly.
They would never do such a thing, not in my city of dreaming spires.
Even my communist friends always showed impeccable manners.
His wet eyes were clouded.
Give the whole thing a chance.
I'm sure they're just teasing you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also Tory supporters, had given in to the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week where another history tutor had seriously claimed that I was “an enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Although I was secretly crushed with shame, I admitted that my parents had “brainwashed me” and called her “old jerk.”
The relief lasted only a short time.
It was my father who put the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At the time, he was writing two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes, my bunnies gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
You are welcome to call me a whiny cock.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer from such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragically, it was Oxford – a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved call for equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to celebrity"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino - Master of Couture", which opened this week in London, ABC talks with Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous customers of the Italian fashion maker.
Somerset House, the former residence of Isabel I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition on Valentino Garavani.
This was acknowledged by the designer at the opening of "Valentino - Master of Couture", a grandiose retrospective, for which more than 130 haute couture dresses were put together, created by his "maison" over the last 50 years.
“I love this palace,” he says with his unmistakable Italian accent.
This exhibition is the conclusion of a story whose only protagonist is "il signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without his distinguished clientele.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the stuffy and distant world of nobility.
In the first hall of this exhibition, which will be on view until March 3, there are a large number of private letters and photographs with the signature of the most exquisite aristocracy, from Princess Salimah Aga Khan to Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margarita of England to Lord Snowdon.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise from the humble fashion designer in the town of Voghera in northern Italy to the idol of the international jet set.
To be in love with the nobility does not have to be a disadvantage.
“At least they don’t kick their butts out on your gorgeous carpet like some beautiful pop celebrities do,” says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the 60s and 70s, the two lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular, generous and elegant host.
"We were all delighted when we were invited to his house in Gstaad," explains the ex-wife of "Heini" Thyssen, close friends with forgotten beauties such as Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred the elegance of celebrity.
And yet he is a star.
Valeria Mazza, in a dress by Valentino
Even the Argentine model Valeria Mazza does not forget the charisma of the fashionmaker.
Many years ago, after a fashion show in Piazza di Spagna in Rome, we went to his home for dinner.
We were about 20 people, including Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
At every detail of his apartment, the decoration, the food and the music, one recognized and felt his influence.
“All invited guests felt important and loved,” recalls the “top model” who began her career at the 1995 Haute Couture week in Paris.
“He never goes out of fashion because his designs are works of art,” she concludes.
Fashion show of origin
The life of Garavani is not a story of obsession, but rather of mutual affections.
He likes people with good education and the highest titles, and they love him.
One of the galleries at Somerset House has been transformed into a glorious 60-meter-long catwalk, which suggests a roll-up: the user takes the model's place and walks down the catwalk to admire a dreamlike "audience" wearing masterpieces by Valentino, such as the dress that Jackie Kennedy wore for her wedding with Arist<0xC3><0xB3>teles Onassis, the dress that was worn by the Viist<0xC3><0xB3>tele.
In this audience of fashion dolls, names such as that of Sibilla de Luxemburgo, Gloria of Thurn and Taxis, Mette-Marit of Norway, Rosario of Bulgaria or Sof<0xC3><0xAD>a of Habsburg shine.
Naty Abascal and the Fashionmaker, 2006
Many of these customers say that the first Valentino is like the first love, "unforgettable".
I can still remember perfectly.
It was a pants, a shirt, a vest type "gillette" and a jacket from the autumn/winter collection 1971-1972.
“It was a gift from him,” says Naty Abascal, one of the designer’s muses.
"I prefer him to everyone else because of his great love for women and because he highlights our beauty," added the ex-duchess of Feria.
I like the colors he uses very much; they have a lot of light and underline the face.
The proportions are perfect.
Also the princess and opinion leader in the fashion Patricia della Giovampaola d'Arenberg can't forget the first time she wore a Valentino.
When I lived in Italy as a teenager, I dreamed of finally having the age and opportunity to wear one of his evening dresses...
At the end of the 90s it finally happened.
I bought my first Valentino dress for a party in the castle of my cousin, Prince Edouard de Ligne.
It was a red dress with a flying skirt and a draped top with a cleavage that lives up to its name.
"It was a dream come true," says Rodrigo d'Arenberg's widow.
“Valentino does not depend on fashion, his obsession is timeless,” explains this Italian aristocrat who lives between Par<0xC3><0xAD>s, New York and Buenos Aires.
The Princess D'Arenberg keeps her evening dresses of the fashionmaker "with absolute care", "because a dress is not only a dress, but also the memories associated with it".
The "King" of Fashion
The grand finale of the exhibition at Somerset House is Marie-Chantal Miller’s wedding dress for her wedding to Pablo de Grecia in 1995.
Four months of work and 25 "ragazze" (as the fashion designer called his seamstresses) were necessary to make this ivory silk dress with pearls, twelve different embroidery and a four and a half meter long tail.
According to the journalist Suzy Menkes, the supreme authority of the trade press, this dress was a milestone in haute couture at the end of the 20th century, "the return to the customers of the supreme society".
For years, marred with the "savoir-<0xC3><0xAA>tre" of the elite, Valentino is now their best specimen.
Cavaliere di Gran Croce (the highest award of Italy), Cavaliere del Lavoro, Commandeur de L'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres, awarded with the Legion of Honor, accumulates Garavani as many honors as any of the husbands of his clients.
"I have always noticed his refinement, his calmness, his well-groomed and perfect appearance," admits D'Arenberg.
I last saw him at a gala dinner at the Museum de Orsay a month ago.
He was sitting at the table of Countess Jacqueline de Ribes, a very good friend of mine.
"He was flawless; time leaves no traces on him".
And this is what a princess says...
The most difficult profession in the world: the human work animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and their health if they carry 70 kilos of sulfur over the steep, stony paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he must descend every day to the bottom of his crater, where the sulphurous gas flowing out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the sloping stone paths.
While it’s only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2,386 meters, the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb at turtle speed, keeping balance and carefully taking their steps so they don’t slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur they mine.
Once at the top, they make their way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tiringly heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters.
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who has been exploiting the occurrences in the volcano since 1960 and (never better) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for every kilo of sulfur.
