Beginning of the course that studies the "end of the world"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, virus and germs, and global warming.
Every semester, when the professor of religion decided to hold a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible fishing hook: the end of the Mayan calendar’s “long backwards count” on December 21, which many people believed meant the end of the world.
But Charmé had no idea what to expect over the next two months: the destructive hurricane Sandy, which some have called "Deudarmaggedon," as well as a growing conflict involving Israel, the place Christian theorists believe the apocalypse begins.
"I didn't realize that this will be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey) this week.
If someone were to analyze what happened in the world today as if we were thirty days away from it, this would be a really good period.
And he reminds us that the bad is good for those with an apocalyptic mentality.
And he’s not the only professor who offers courses on the “end of the world” this semester, which should actually be the last in history.
In Temple, Professor Barry Vacker gives the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World."
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, virus and germs, and global warming.
“We analyze why these ideas spread over time,” he said, as well as the way hypothetical scenarios are offered that lead to a particular human behavior.
If nuclear material gets into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, the students analyzed films with apocalyptic content and looked at how they compare to real life.
"I've been trying to inform students about what's possible, likely, credible, and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of the University of Pennsylvania, Professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an attending Professor of Art History and Anthropology, formed a team to offer a course called simply “The End of the World.”
“We don’t pick up 2012 so we always have the option to hold the course again in case the world doesn’t go down,” Restall said.
Despite the "prominent doom," students must study, create projects, and take part in final exams.
In Penn State, the final exam is held on the eve of the apocalypse, which is why students have no other chance than to “continue working until nightfall, where the world is supposed to end,” Restall said.
The courses were very popular.
“In two hours, there were no more places,” Restall said of his course for high-average students, which filled with 35 students.
For weeks before the start of the semester, we received e-mails from students asking if there were still places available.
Students, for their part, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It’s fascinating to see what people are doing to comfort themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in Rutgers-Camden for religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey.
The apocalyptic sect or religious mentality is actually only a matter of consolation or its absence.
25-year-old psychology and nursing student Will Wekesa said he had seen all the apocalyptic films.
"I have never heard of a class where this is being taught," he said.
I'm enjoying it.
But none of the students surveyed – and less so a professor – declared to believe in the last date of December 21.
“Our first project dealt with the prophecy of the Mayans, and in a certain way we discredit them,” said Julie Zeglen, a student last year at Temple, 21 years old and from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it’s just a key point in the calendar, Restall said.
He notes, however, that there is an apocalyptic fear in Western society that dates back several centuries when people reacted to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The internet has increased this speculation.
“People elsewhere don’t think that way,” he says.
This is mainly the case in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at the University of La Salle, who is teaching in the Philippines this year, quickly responds to the question of whether he would know a course on the “end of the world” there.
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world," he wrote as a hint of an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall pointed out that over the years many days have been spoken of by the Last Judgment, saying that if nothing happens on December 21, “people immediately think of a new date” or philosophizing about it, that December 21 was the beginning of a seven-year period after which the end of the world would come.
Students and professors take this date lightly.
Several said they would like to go to celebrations about “the end of the world.”
“Maybe I’ll call a few friends so we can laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
